---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Base title="The Empty State Problem" section={5}>
  <SectionHeader n={5} title="The Empty State Problem" meta="~400w" />

  <div class="prose">

    <p>
      What does a dashboard look like when everything is fine?
    </p>

    <p>
      Take a moment with that question, because most dashboards have no answer to it.
      They look exactly the same whether everything is fine or something is catastrophically
      wrong. The numbers update. The charts repaint. The tiles sit in their grid, unchanged
      in character regardless of what the values actually say. There is no difference in
      the dashboard's posture between "normal Tuesday" and "something just broke."
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      <p>A good dashboard should be boring when things are normal and loud when
      they aren't. Almost none are designed this way.</p>
    </PullQuote>

    <p>
      This is a catastrophic design failure, and it is almost universal. The entire premise
      of monitoring is that the instrument should demand attention when attention is warranted
      and stay out of the way when it is not. A dashboard that looks the same in all states
      is not a monitoring tool. It is a static display. It requires the viewer to bring their
      own calibration — to already know what normal looks like, to already know which numbers
      matter and in what direction, to already know what threshold constitutes a problem.
      It outsources all the intelligence to the human and provides none of its own.
    </p>

    <p>
      The empty state problem is really the default state problem. Most dashboards have
      only one visual state: numbers present. They have not been designed for the states
      that matter most: everything-nominal, one-thing-off, something-urgent, unknown-data.
      These states call for radically different visual treatments. A dashboard where all
      thresholds are green should feel calm. A dashboard where one metric has crossed
      a threshold should feel slightly wrong — a different weight or temperature to it.
      A dashboard with a critical alert should demand to be looked at.
    </p>

    <Annotation label="Design principle">
      Design for the boring state first. The dashboard you see on ninety-eight percent
      of normal days should be visually quiet — it should not make you work to confirm
      that nothing needs your attention. The cost of vigilance should be nearly zero
      when nothing is wrong.
    </Annotation>

    <p>
      This requires threshold design, which requires the work from <a href={`${base}section/2`}>§2</a> — actually defining
      what normal looks like, what out-of-range means, and what the response is. You cannot
      build a dashboard that knows when to be quiet without first deciding what loud means.
      Most organisations have not done this work, so they build dashboards that are always
      medium-loud — always showing the same level of information regardless of urgency —
      which produces a kind of ambient numbness. Everything looks like it might matter.
      So nothing does.
    </p>

    <p>
      The fix is conceptually simple and operationally hard. For each metric: define normal.
      Define the threshold at which someone should pay attention. Define the threshold at
      which someone should act. Design the dashboard to be visually inert when all metrics
      are in the normal band, and to escalate — visually, in weight, in contrast, in
      prominence — when they leave it. The ideal end state is a dashboard that a reasonable
      person can dismiss in three seconds when everything is fine, and cannot ignore when
      something is not.
    </p>

  </div>
</Base>
